What “persistent memory” means in a provable sense

You don’t prove “memory” abstractly. You prove properties of a system that stores and retrieves information.

Anchor it to something concrete like:

* State Space
* Information Theory

⸻

Step 1 — Define the system

Let:

* S = set of system states
* M = memory store
* W: S \rightarrow M (write)
* R: M \rightarrow S (read)

Now you’re in formal territory.

⸻

Step 2 — Define “persistence” precisely

Here’s a testable definition:

A memory system is persistent if information written at time t can be recovered at time t+k within bounded loss.

Formal version:

\| R(W(s)) - s \| \le \epsilon

That’s already something you can measure.

⸻

Step 3 — Add your actual twist (Pantheon layer)

Your system isn’t just storage—it’s transformative memory.

So define:

* Transformations T
* Cost d(T)
* Invariant I

Now you can state a real claim:

Memory is persistent under transformation if invariant information survives transformation chains.

Formal:

I(T_n \circ \cdots \circ T_1 (s)) = I(s)

Now you’ve turned “meaning persistence” into an invariance problem.

